-! # how to errors: 003-lit-str-unterminated.zo
-!
-! @cmd: `zo build 003-lit-str-unterminated.zo`
-!
-! Every string must be closed with a matching `"`. 
-!
-! If you forget, the compiler "swallows" everything after the opening 
-! quote—including your semicolons and closing braces. You get "two  errors for
-! the price of one." This is why we always fix the **first** error in the list
-! first.

fun main() {
  -- The quote below is never closed.
  -- Everything until the end of the file is now just "text" to zo.
  imu x: str = "this string never closes;
}

-! ## the diagnostic map.
-!
-! Notice how ariadne highlights the opening double quote and points to the end
-! of the line. Because the string never ended, the compiler never saw the
-! closing brace of your function.
-!
-! ## try this.
-!
-!   1. Add the closing quote after the word closes.
-!   2. Both errors will disappear—the string was the root cause.
-!   3. Try putting a newline inside the string. Does zo allow multi-line
-!      strings, or does it throw another error?
-!      (Hint: Most systems languages require a special syntax for multi-line).

-- EXPECTED OUTPUT:
-- [E0001] Error: Unterminated string literal
--     ╭─[ 003-lit-str-unterminated.zo:15:16 ]
--     │
--  15 │   imu x: str = "this string never closes;
--     │                ─────────────┬────────────
--     │                             ╰────────────── string literal started here
--     │
--     │ Help: Add a closing quote to terminate the string
-- ────╯
